In Japan, you can deliver the package to a convenience store near you and then pick it up from the counter there anytime of the day. I haven't actually tried that, however, as I mostly schedule my packages to be delivered at a specific time slot (e.g. 8-12, 12-14, 14-16... etc). Scheduling will cause a slight delay when compared to the fast shipping provided by Prime (something like half a day later or so).

@HB45175\xa0I live in an apartment in Seattle and US post drop the mail off in a mailbox in the parking lot and anything that won't fit they put outside my door even if I am not at home. Rarely they hide it behind a plant or under the welcome mat but I have never had a package stolen in 4+ years here so it works fine even for big items like a laptop which they can't hide.\xa0
@Fanta711 You go to the petrol station or grocery store and they'll send it for you.
@Jerry Law Gotta say the quality of food in the convenience stores in Japan (lunch boxes, sandwiches and fried food among others) is surprisingly great. 7-Eleven's onigiri are just awesome.

@Jerry Law While they are quite convenient, I usually try to avoid buying by from them since they are more expensive than supermarkets and grocery shops (which usually close between 7-8PM with some closing around 10PM).
@Jerry Law The thing about those convenience stores in Japan is that they are open 24/7. Otherwise, it won't mean much to forward the packages there.
@HB45175 Wait, what? If the postal service closed all its offices, how do you send stuff?

Here in Sweden the postal service closed all their offices and regardless of what you order it'll be sent to a pickup location (which is usually a grocery store or a petrol station). DHL/Schenker etc and whatnot use the same system.
Yes there are a few restrictions. It's only items Fulfilled by Amazon and I've noticed pre-orders can't be sent there either (or Vinyl albums because they are "too big").
